The KwaZulu-Natal MEC of Transport, Community Safety and Liaison, Mxolisi Kaunda, has called upon road users to be vigilant, following deaths on the roads. On 27 June, a crash on the N3 near Pinetown, claimed the  lives of three males and a female. It was reported that a taxi driver lost control after being obstructed by a stationary truck. In the same accident, two passengers were critically injured and 11 passengers sustained minor injuries. The critical passengers were airlifted to Gateway and Lenmed ethekwini Hospitals. The other passengers were transported by ambulance to  nearby hospitals. Kaunda has conveyed his  condolences to the families of the deceased and wished the injured a speedy recovery. “It is disheartening to learn that innocent lives were lost in a crash that could have been avoided. We urge motorists to be extra vigilant and to observe the rules. Motorists must keep to the speed limit and slow down in good time when the need arises ,” he said. Police have opened four culpable homicide dockets.